defs.name: cell
defs.docs: Helper module for some internals, most users don't need to interact with it.

defs.name: InvalidBorrow
defs.docs: Marker struct for an invalid borrow error

defs.name: Ref
defs.docs: An immutable reference to data in a `TrustCell`.

defs.name: RefMut
defs.docs: A mutable reference to data in a `TrustCell`.

defs.name: TrustCell
defs.docs: A custom cell container that is a `RefCell` with thread-safety.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Create a new cell, similar to `RefCell::new`

defs.name: borrow
defs.docs: Get an immutable reference to the inner data.

defs.name: try_borrow
defs.docs: Get an immutable reference to the inner data.

defs.name: borrow_mut
defs.docs: Get a mutable reference to the inner data.

defs.name: try_borrow_mut
defs.docs: Get a mutable reference to the inner data.

defs.name: get_mut
defs.docs: Gets exclusive access to the inner value, bypassing the Cell.

defs.name: AsyncDispatcher
defs.docs: Like, `Dispatcher` but works asynchronously.

defs.name: dispatch
defs.docs:
Dispatches the systems asynchronously.
 Does not execute thread local systems.

defs.name: wait
defs.docs:
Waits for all the asynchronously dispatched systems to finish
 and executes thread local systems (if there are any).

defs.name: wait_without_tl
defs.docs:
Waits for all the asynchronously dispatched systems to finish
 without executing thread local systems.

defs.name: running
defs.docs: Checks if any of the asynchronously dispatched systems are running.

defs.name: res
defs.docs: Returns the resources.

defs.name: mut_res
defs.docs: Returns the resources mutable.

defs.name: DispatcherBuilder
defs.docs: Builder for the [`Dispatcher`].

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates a new `DispatcherBuilder` by using the `Default` implementation.

defs.name: with
defs.value: fn <T> (mut self, system: T, name: &str, dep: &[&str]) -> Self
defs.docs:
Adds a new system with a given name and a list of dependencies.
 Please note that the dependency should be added before
 you add the depending system.

defs.name: add
defs.value: fn <T> (&mut self, system: T, name: &str, dep: &[&str]) -> ()
defs.docs:
Adds a new system with a given name and a list of dependencies.
 Please note that the dependency should be added before
 you add the depending system.

defs.name: with_thread_local
defs.docs: Adds a new thread local system.

defs.name: add_thread_local
defs.docs: Adds a new thread local system.

defs.name: with_barrier
defs.docs:
Inserts a barrier which assures that all systems
 added before the barrier are executed before the ones
 after this barrier.

defs.name: add_barrier
defs.docs:
Inserts a barrier which assures that all systems
 added before the barrier are executed before the ones
 after this barrier.

defs.name: with_pool
defs.docs:
Attach a rayon thread pool to the builder
 and use that instead of creating one.

defs.name: add_pool
defs.docs:
Attach a rayon thread pool to the builder
 and use that instead of creating one.

defs.name: print_par_seq
defs.docs:
Prints the equivalent system graph
 that can be easily used to get the graph using the `seq!` and `par!`
 macros. This is only recommended for advanced users.

defs.name: build
defs.docs: Builds the `Dispatcher`.

defs.name: build_async
defs.docs: Builds an async dispatcher.

defs.name: Dispatcher
defs.docs:
The dispatcher struct, allowing
 systems to be executed in parallel.

defs.name: setup
defs.docs:
Sets up all the systems which means they are gonna add default values for the resources
 they need.

defs.name: dispose
defs.docs:
Calls the `dispose` method of all systems and allows them to release
 external resources. It is common this method removes components and
 / or resources from the `Resources` which are associated with external
 resources.

defs.name: dispatch
defs.docs:
Dispatch all the systems with given resources and context
 and then run thread local systems.

defs.name: dispatch_par
defs.docs:
Dispatches the systems (except thread local systems)
 in parallel given the resources to operate on.

defs.name: dispatch_seq
defs.docs: Dispatches the systems (except thread local systems) sequentially.

defs.name: dispatch_thread_local
defs.docs: Dispatch only thread local systems sequentially.

defs.name: max_threads
defs.docs:
This method returns the largest amount of threads this dispatcher
 can make use of. This is mainly for debugging purposes so you can see
 how well your systems can make use of multi-threading.

defs.name: Nil
defs.docs: The "leave node" for the `Par` / `Seq` list.

defs.name: Par
defs.docs:
Runs two tasks in parallel.
 These two tasks are called `head` and `tail`
 in the following documentation.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates a new `Par` struct, with the tail being a no-op.

defs.name: with
defs.value: fn <T> (self, sys: T) -> Par<Par<H, T>, Nil>
defs.docs:
Adds `sys` as the second job and returns a new `Par` struct
 with the previous struct as head and a no-op tail.

defs.name: ParSeq
defs.docs:
A dispatcher intended to be used with
 `Par` and `Seq`  structures.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Creates a new `ParSeq` dispatcher.
 `run` is usually created by using the `par!` / `seq!`
 macros.

defs.name: setup
defs.docs:
Sets up `res` for `dispatch`ing.
 This will add default values for required resources by calling `System::setup`.

defs.name: dispatch
defs.docs:
Dispatches the systems using `res`.
 This doesn't call any virtual functions.

defs.name: RunWithPool
defs.docs:
Similar to `RunNow` except additionally taking in a rayon::ThreadPool
 for parallelism.

defs.name: setup
defs.docs: Sets up `Resources` for a later call to `run`.

defs.name: run
defs.docs:
Runs the system/group of systems. Possibly in parallel depending
 on how the structure is set up.

defs.name: reads
defs.docs:
Accumulates the necessary read/shared resources from the
 systems in this group.

defs.name: writes
defs.docs:
Accumulates the necessary write/exclusive resources from the
 systems in this group.

defs.name: Seq
defs.docs:
Runs two tasks sequentially.
 These two tasks are called `head` and `tail`
 in the following documentation.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates a new `Seq` struct, with the tail being a no-op.

defs.name: with
defs.value: fn <T> (self, sys: T) -> Seq<Seq<H, T>, Nil>
defs.docs:
Adds `sys` as the second job and returns a new `Seq` struct
 with the previous struct as head and a no-op tail.

defs.name: CastFrom
defs.docs:
Helper trait for the `MetaTable`.
 This trait is required to be implemented for a trait to be compatible with the meta table.

defs.name: cast
defs.docs: Casts an immutable `T` reference to a trait object.

defs.name: cast_mut
defs.docs: Casts a mutable `T` reference to a trait object.

defs.name: MetaIter
defs.docs: An iterator for the `MetaTable`.

defs.name: MetaIterMut
defs.docs: A mutable iterator for the `MetaTable`.

defs.name: MetaTable
defs.docs: The `MetaTable` which allows to store object-safe trait implementations for resources.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates a new `MetaTable`.

defs.name: register
defs.docs:
Registers a resource `R` that implements the trait `T`.
 This just needs some instance of type `R` to retrieve the vtable.
 It doesn't have to be the same object you're calling `get` with later.

defs.name: get
defs.docs:
Tries to convert `res` to a trait object of type `&T`.
 If `res` doesn't have an implementation for `T` (or it wasn't registered),
 this will return `None`.

defs.name: get_mut
defs.value: fn <'a> (&self, res: &'a Resource) -> Option<&'a mut T>
defs.docs:
Tries to convert `res` to a trait object of type `&mut T`.
 If `res` doesn't have an implementation for `T` (or it wasn't registered),
 this will return `None`.

defs.name: iter
defs.value: fn <'a> (&'a self, res: &'a Resources) -> MetaIter<'a, T>
defs.docs: Iterates all resources that implement `T` and were registered.

defs.name: iter_mut
defs.value: fn <'a> (&'a self, res: &'a Resources) -> MetaIterMut<'a, T>
defs.docs: Iterates all resources that implement `T` and were registered mutably.

defs.name: Read
defs.docs: Allows to fetch a resource in a system immutably.

defs.name: Write
defs.docs: Allows to fetch a resource in a system mutably.

defs.name: ReadExpect
defs.docs:
Allows to fetch a resource in a system immutably.
 **This will panic if the resource does not exist.**
 Usage of `Read` or `Option<Read>` is therefore recommended.

defs.name: WriteExpect
defs.docs:
Allows to fetch a resource in a system mutably.
 **This will panic if the resource does not exist.**
 Usage of `Write` or `Option<Write>` is therefore recommended.

defs.name: Entry
defs.docs:
An entry to a resource of the `Resources` struct.
 This is similar to the Entry API found in the standard library.

defs.name: or_insert
defs.docs: Returns this entry's value, inserts and returns `v` otherwise.

defs.name: or_insert_with
defs.docs: Returns this entry's value, inserts and returns the return value of `f` otherwise.

defs.name: DefaultProvider
defs.docs: A `SetupHandler` that simply uses the default implementation.

defs.name: SetupHandler
defs.docs: A setup handler performing the fetching of `T`.

defs.name: setup
defs.docs: Sets up `Resources` for fetching `T`.

defs.name: PanicHandler
defs.docs:
A setup handler that simply does nothing and thus will cause a panic on fetching.
 The panic will provide the type name if the `nightly` feature of shred is enabled.

defs.name: Fetch
defs.docs: Allows to fetch a resource in a system immutably.

defs.name: FetchMut
defs.docs: Allows to fetch a resource in a system mutably.

defs.name: Resource
defs.docs:
A resource defines a set of data
 which can only be accessed according
 to Rust's typical borrowing model (one writer xor multiple readers).

defs.name: ResourceId
defs.docs:
The id of a [`Resource`],
 which is a tuple struct with a type
 id and an additional resource id (represented with a `usize`).

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates a new resource id from a given type.

defs.name: Resources
defs.docs:
A resource container, which provides methods to access to
 the contained resources.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates a new, empty resource container.

defs.name: insert
defs.docs:
Inserts a resource into this container. If the resource existed before, it will be
 overwritten.

defs.name: has_value
defs.docs: Returns true if the specified resource type `R` exists in `self`.

defs.name: has_value_raw
defs.docs: Returns true if the specified resource type exists in `self`.

defs.name: entry
defs.docs: Returns an entry for the resource with type `R`.

defs.name: fetch
defs.docs: Fetches the resource with the specified type `T` or panics if it doesn't exist.

defs.name: try_fetch
defs.docs:
Like `fetch`, but returns an `Option` instead of inserting a default value
 in case the resource does not exist.

defs.name: fetch_mut
defs.docs: Fetches the resource with the specified type `T` mutably.

defs.name: try_fetch_mut
defs.docs:
Like `fetch_mut`, but returns an `Option` instead of inserting a default value
 in case the resource does not exist.

defs.name: try_fetch_internal
defs.docs: Internal function for fetching resources, should only be used if you know what you're doing.

defs.name: get_mut
defs.docs:
Retrieves a resource without fetching, which is cheaper, but only available with
 `&mut self`.

defs.name: get_mut_raw
defs.value: fn (&mut self, id: TypeId) -> Option<&mut Resource>
defs.docs:
Retrieves a resource without fetching, which is cheaper, but only available with
 `&mut self`.

defs.name: Accessor
defs.docs:
A trait for accessing read/write multiple resources from a system. This can be used
 to create dynamic systems that don't specify what they fetch at compile-time.

defs.name: try_new
defs.docs:
Tries to create a new instance of this type. This one returns `Some` in case there is a
 default, otherwise the system needs to override `System::accessor`.

defs.name: reads
defs.docs:
A list of [`ResourceId`]s the bundle
 needs read access to in order to
 build the target resource bundle.

defs.name: writes
defs.docs:
A list of [`ResourceId`]s the bundle
 needs write access to in order to
 build the target resource bundle.

defs.name: Ref
defs.docs: A reference to an accessor.

defs.name: Owned
defs.docs: An owned accessor.

defs.name: AccessorCow
defs.docs: Either an `Accessor` of the system `T` or a reference to it.

defs.name: RunNow
defs.docs: Trait for fetching data and running systems. Automatically implemented for systems.

defs.name: run_now
defs.docs: Runs the system now.

defs.name: setup
defs.docs: Sets up `Resources` for a later call to `run_now`.

defs.name: dispose
defs.docs: Performs clean up that requires resources from the `Resources`.

defs.name: System
defs.docs: A `System`, executed with a set of required [`Resource`]s.

defs.name: SystemData
defs.docs: The resource bundle required to execute this system.

defs.name: run
defs.docs:
Executes the system with the required system
 data.

defs.name: running_time
defs.docs:
Returns a hint how long the system needs for running.
 This is used to optimize the way they're executed (might
 allow more parallelization).

defs.name: accessor
defs.docs: Return the accessor from the [`SystemData`].

defs.name: setup
defs.docs: Sets up the `Resources` using `Self::SystemData::setup`.

defs.name: dispose
defs.docs: Performs clean up that requires resources from the `Resources`.

defs.name: SystemData
defs.docs:
A static system data that can specify its dependencies at statically (at compile-time).
 Most system data is a `SystemData`, the `DynamicSystemData` type is only needed for very special
 setups.

defs.name: setup
defs.docs: Sets up the system data for fetching it from the `Resources`.

defs.name: fetch
defs.docs:
Fetches the system data from `Resources`. Note that this is only specified for one concrete
 lifetime `'a`, you need to implement the `SystemData` trait for every possible
 lifetime.

defs.name: reads
defs.docs: Returns all read dependencies as fetched from `Self::fetch`.

defs.name: writes
defs.docs: Returns all write dependencies as fetched from `Self::fetch`.

defs.name: StaticAccessor
defs.docs: The static accessor that is used for `SystemData`.

defs.name: DynamicSystemData
defs.docs:
A struct implementing system data indicates that it bundles some resources which are required
 for the execution.

defs.name: Accessor
defs.docs:
The accessor of the `SystemData`, which specifies the read and write dependencies and does
 the fetching.

defs.name: setup
defs.docs: Sets up `Resources` for fetching this system data.

defs.name: fetch
defs.docs:
Creates a new resource bundle
 by fetching the required resources
 from the [`Resources`] struct.
